nt||fp|1|ht|c|cs|2|cp|2|AT|^b@2Let's consider the case where you have 4 card support and 9+ HCP, (10+ dummy points: limit raise(+) values)
You should bid 2NT, the "Jordan convention". 
So 1@h (X) 2NT means  - "limit raise or better with a 4-card support"

What's really nice about this bid is opener immediately knows the most important 2 facts about your hand. 
Point count and 4 card support
 
There are 2 schools of thought on what to do with 7-9 points and 4 card support. 

Bergen uses "BROMAD" - Bergen Raises of Major After Double. 
Here is how it works. 

1@h (x) 
- With 7-9 points and 3 card support, bid 2@C . 
- With 7-9 points and 4 card support, bid 2@d

Example: @sxx, @hKxxx, @dQJxx, @cQxx.
Bid 2@d over 1@h (x). 
This is 100% non-standard and requires you and partner to discuss carefully
With @sxx, @hKxx, @dQJxx, @cQxxx, bid 2@c

Note that if you use this convention, you raise 1@h to 2@h with 3 trump and junk|
