mitche: The difference is that a 9 card fit is vastly better than an 8 card fit. 
You are "law protected" with a 9 card fit to bid to the 3 level... 
Bergen says that the 9th trump is the most underrated card in the deck
Wayne_LV:  I realize that but when does it make a diff between bidding game and not bidding game if you have the  points?
mitche: When someone doubles, announcing an opening hand and shortness in your bid suit, you can expect a bad trump split, Wayne, so that 5-4 fit is crucial in deciding whether to bid to  the 3 or 4 level
In my experience, bidding to game on an 8 card fit after a double requires something extra.. 

If I am using BROMAD, I will raise 1@h to 2@h with any 3 card support and any 4-6 point hand
With 0-3 points, I am not eager to punish pard
But that 4 card raise to 3 is really, really effective. 
It's almost as disruptive as an opening 3 bid.

So we have covered 3 and 4 card raises
What if you do not have a raise?
What if you do not have a fit and you do have a lot for points (say 10 or more)?
You REDOUBLE
This says, "good hand, but no 4 card support.."
It is something you can find on the convention card under the box "redouble implies no fit" and is not alertable
You might have 3 card support, in which case you will raise later. 
But the redouble says, "we own the hand" and we expect to be able to punish the opponents if they get too frisky
In principle, yes it means no support. 
But what do you do with @sxx, @hKxx, @dAxxx, @cAJ10x ?|
